observations.recommendation:
We reiterated our recommendation and Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive require:

the coordination between the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer/General Services Officer towards the full implementation of the perpetual inventory method in the recording of all Inventory Accounts to ensure proper accounting and promote better control in the receipt and issuance of supplies and materials;

the MAO and MGSO to maintain the prescribed ledger cards and stock cards, respectively, for each type of Inventory, keep track the actual Supplies Inventory on hand and reconcile the balances of the two inventory records.

We recommended and Management agreed to:

delegate the receipt and acknowledgement of the donations whether cash or in-kind to the Municipal Treasurer’s Office;

take heed of the basic controls in the receipt, recording, inventory, storage and distribution of all donations received even in the midst of a crisis;

submit the required reports together with the supporting documents;


require the Committee in charge of the Physical Inventory to include In-kind Donations received by the Municipality in the physical count and Inventory Report; 

record the cash donations received under the Trust Liabilities – DRRMF account as mandated by section IV.B.7 of COA Circular 2014-002; and 

maintain a separate bank account with an authorized government depository bank (AGDB) where cash donations are to be deposited.

We recommended and Management agreed to:

require the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to conduct a regular reconciliation of balances under the Cash in Bank account; 



require the MT and other collecting officers to update their individual cashbooks regularly and indicate recapitulations/totals for each month for easier review;

submit AFs and corresponding RCDs on the 10th day of the following month to COA for a timely review; and 



exert best effort to validate and reconcile balances between cashbooks and ledgers, and make necessary adjustments once reconciling items have been verified and substantiated.

We reiterated our recommendation and Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive require the:

Inventory Team to (i) conduct complete annual physical inventory-taking of PPE by type and submit a complete Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) not later than January 31 of each year; and

Municipal General Services Officer to maintain property cards for property, plant and equipment and effect its reconciliation with the ledger cards of the Municipal Accounting Office.

We also reiterated our recommendation and Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive direct the Municipal Accountant to: 

investigate the discrepancy noted between the balances in the SL and schedules and effect the necessary adjustments to reduce it to minimum, if not zero out;



ensure that all government property officially received by the Municipality are accounted for and taken up in the books at acquisition cost or appraised value;



coordinate with the Municipal Engineering Office with regards to the cost of partially completed infrastructure projects as of year-end and the breakdown of cost of each completed project lumped in one amount to ensure complete, accurate and timely recording thereof;

ensure monthly recognition of depreciation expense of all the PPE accounts;

make the necessary adjustments in the books to correct all  erroneous recording/classification noted;  and

adopt all the principles prescribed in PPSAS 17 for proper accounting of the Municipality’s PPE and for a fair presentation of the asset accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended and  Management agreed to:

submit additional supporting documents for the conversion of Tinajero Elementary School--₱22,050.00, truck rental--₱14,600.00, and medicines--₱289,595.80;

submit an explanation for the incomplete information provided in the SDs for the purchase of groceries amounting to ₱59,400.00;

require the Municipal Accountant to verify completeness of attached SDs before payment is made;

require the concerned department to update the Municipality's website and make the necessary posting as part of their public disclosure requirements; and

return to the National Treasury the unutilized balance of ₱11,313.18 and the amount of ₱28,750.00, which is not among the allowable expenditures using the BGCM, after the lifting of State of Calamity.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to require the:
MDRRMC to prepare and submit the Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund Investment Plan (LDRRMFIP) indicating the (i) detailed PPAs and the corresponding appropriation classified as either Maintenance and Other Operating Expenses (MOOE) or Capital Outlay (CO); and 

(ii) under a separate caption, the list of projects and activities charged to the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years for ease of monitoring of project implementation and evaluation; 

MDRRMC ensure that the LDRRMF be strictly utilized for the implementation of projects and activities for disaster prevention and mitigation, preparedness, response and rehabilitation and recovery;

Municipal Accountant to (i) comply with the monthly submission of the Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF; 

(ii) and maintain corresponding Subsidiary Ledger for each type of Disaster Response and Rescue Equipment; and 

(iii) ensure that the amount and details of the unexpended balance of the LDRRMF is discussed in the Notes to Financial Statements.

We also recommended that the amount irregularly charged against LDRRMF be restored to LDRMMF.

We recommended that the Management require the:

(a) Inventory Committee to conduct an inventory of the local roads under the jurisdiction of the Municipality and render a Report on the Physical count of the Road Networks System;

 (b) Municipal General Service Officer to (i) render a Report on Local Road Network and Road Map; and (ii) keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components;

(c) Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal General Service Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects; 

(d) Municipal Accountant to (i) prepare the JEV to record the beginning balance of the local road network and its components; (ii) prepare and maintain a Local Road Network Ledger Card; (iii) keep and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network; (iv) prepare a lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each component at the end of the year.

We recommended that the Local Finance Committee 

(a) conduct frequent analysis and study in forecasting revenues/income to further improve targets set for collections; 

(b) through the Municipal Assessor, initiate measures to further update values of property and coordinate with the Province of Pampanga regarding the required revision of accounts on real properties in the Municipality; 

(c) conduct tax mapping of businesses in a more frequent manner and implement strategies that would encourage business owners to pay their taxes like the recognition of top taxpayers, among others; 

(d) conduct a study on the continuous decrease of quarry collections in close coordination with the new management, giving importance on the enhancement of controls in monitoring;

 (e) through the MTO, employ new strategies and coordinate at the barangay level for a wider reach of taxpayers; and 

(f) consider increasing payment methods such as, but not limited to, bank payments, mall-based kiosk, and payment centers at barangays.

We recommended that Management 

(a) require the job-order personnel who failed to present themselves in our office to personally report with their valid ID; 

(b)  require the JOs assigned at the legislative department to register and employ the mandatory use of the biometric system; 



(c) limit positions in core offices who perform the functions of regular employee; and


 (d) require all department heads to carefully evaluate or assess the need for a job order personnel with due consideration on their qualification to the job requirement.

We recommended that Management :

(a) assure that proper and adequate planning on the utilization of resources is done and prioritize and review planned projects prior to implementation; 

(b) secure the building premises to protect it from possible destruction and loss caused by outside elements; 

(c) submit justification on the continuous non-usage of the structure; 

(d) schedule a meeting with officials concerned to determine which office or department is practically suited to stay at the said multi-purpose hall so that the property will be taken care of properly and further deterioration will be prevented.

We reiterated our recommendation that the Local Chief Executive require the MTO to:

submit the RPCI in the correct format and submit to the Auditor within the prescribed deadline;

consolidate weekly the RIS using the SSMI and submit to the Accounting office for recording of issued supplies;  

coordinate with the Municipal Accounting Office in reconciling their records of the Inventory on a per category basis; and

assign a separate full time employee to handle management of office supplies.


We also reiterated our recommendation that the LCE require the Municipal Accountant to maintain Supplies Ledger Card for each type of Inventory and update their record in keeping track the actual Supplies Inventory on hand.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Treasurer:

refrain from granting cash advances for payment of miscellaneous expenses with no specific and identified purpose;



effect the timely liquidation of cash advances prior to granting the subsequent ones;


set up a petty cash fund to pay for small value and non-recurring expenses; and


see to it that all applicable laws, rules and regulations affecting cash advances and disbursement of funds are strictly adhered to.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the: 

MDRRMC to prepare a comprehensive and detailed LDRRMFIP that will address risk reduction and management system effectively. It should be in accordance with the provisions of R.A. No. 10121 and COA Circular 2012-002 to meet the needs for prevention and mitigation, preparedness, response, rehabilitation and recovery of the Local Government. PPAs shall be listed specifically and allotment for each should be properly classified as either MOOE or CO. It shall also be prepared in the format prescribed by the same Circular and shall include the details of the projects charged to the previous years’ unexpended balance of the DRRMF;

MDRRMO to strictly comply with the preparation of the monthly Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF in accordance with the format prescribed under COA Circular 2012-002, with emphasis on the utilization thereof and the inclusion of balances of previous years’ appropriation transferred to the Special Trust Fund, and submission of the to the Audit Team for timely verification thereof;

Municipal Accountant to follow the provisions of COA Circular 2012-002 as regards the reporting requirements for the DRRMF, specifically the proper transfer of previous year’s unexpended balances of the DRRMF to the Trust Fund; and

Municipal Budget Officer to maintain separate Registry of Appropriations, Allotments and Obligations (RAAO) for the DRRMF on the following: (i) RAAO - for Quick Response Fund; (ii) RAAO-for Maintenance and Other Operating Expenses; and (iii) RAAO- for Capital Outlay.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the Municipal Accountant to: 

completely account for each item composing the PPE; 

investigate on the discrepancy noted and effect the necessary adjustments; 


make provisions for depreciation for all depreciable assets using the correct estimated useful life of assets; 


ensure that all government property officially received by the Municipality are accounted for and taken up in the books at acquisition cost or appraised value; 

(e) reclassify CIP to its appropriate Asset account upon completion of the project; and 




(f) adopt all the principles prescribed in IPSAS 17 for proper accounting of the Municipality’s PPE and for a fair presentation of the asset accounts in the financial statements. 

We also reiterated that the LCE direct the Municipal Treasurer to handle the inventory and monitoring of PPE and ensure that mechanisms are in place to limit opportunities to misappropriate assets or conceal intentional misstatements in the financial statements and to avoid possible loss, theft and misuse of the Municipality’s assets and ensure the: 

regular conduct of physical count of all properties with the prescribed report to be submitted to COA on or before January 31 of each year; and 

proper disposal of unserviceable assets in accordance with applicable rules and regulations.

We recommended that Management:

continue to implement projects which are capital or investment in nature and  implement projects not only those with economic development but also projects with desirable socio and environmental  development to fully attain the objective of the fund;

ensure full completion of the remaining projects identified in the AIP for CY 2018;

ensure that only feasible projects are included in the AIP; and

coordinate with the officials of the DPWH for their proposed projects within the Municipality and concerned Barangays so that possible duplication and overlapping will be readily determined and avoided.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive: 

require the BAC to prepare the Procurement Monitoring Report to be approved by the Local Chief Executive before the same is submitted to the GPPB in printed and electronic format within the prescribed period;

instruct the Municipal Engineer to require from their contractors the issuance of warranty security on all completed projects that will cover the entire defects liability period;

require the BAC to publish or post in public all PPAs being implemented during the year in conspicuous places within the Municipality or in the venue where  the said PPAs  are being carried out  for proper dissemination to the public; and

instruct the BAC to submit a copy of the contracts and purchase others within five days from issuance as required under COA Circular No. 2009-001, together with the bidding documents, BAC resolution, minutes of the proceedings, abstracts, and such other documents necessary in the conduct of auditorial review and in the technical evaluation thereof.

We recommended that management: 

in coordination with the Municipal Treasurer intensify tax collection efforts to generate additional income to finance projects beneficial to its constituents;

take initiatives to find ways and means in order to maximize the exercise of its revenue-raising power and adapt strategic means to improve collection efficiency;

through the Municipal Assessor initiate measures to further update values of property and coordinate with the Province of Pampanga regarding the required revision of accounts on real properties in the Municipality;

conduct tax mapping of businesses in a more frequent manner and implement strategies that would encourage business owners to pay their taxes; 

communicate with the province on discrepancies noted in quarry collections;


conduct a study on the possible use of the RFID system in the quarry site and provide budget in the ensuing year and implement the same; and

take advantage of technology and avail of the BPLS offered by the province or any other MIS that would improve effectiveness and efficiency of the Municipality’s financial operations.

We recommended that management:

continue to improve its performance to further increase amount allocated for personal services and create plantillas for deserving and qualified personnel giving priority to those who have been in long service with the Municipality;

strengthen its recruitment and selection process in hiring job order personnel by reviewing its current workforce, specific work to be done, and objectives before hiring personnel;

require the HR Officer to conduct the proper selection and recruitment process such as the conduct of written, oral, and medical examinations in order to ascertain applicant’s qualifications to all employees including those under the legislative department; and

require all department heads to carefully evaluate or assess the need for job order personnel with due consideration on their fitness to the job requirement.

We reiterated that the Local Chief Executive direct the: 

(a) Inventory Team to  regular conduct physical count of all properties and submit the prescribed report thereon to COA on or before January 31 of each year; 

(b) Disposal Committee to undertake the proper disposal of unserviceable assets in accordance with applicable rules and regulations on disposal procedures; 

(c) Municipal Accountant to observe PPSAS 17 and initiate efforts towards the recognition in the books using cost or appraised value of unrecorded PPE for fair presentation of the accounts in the financial statements.

We also recommended that the LCE direct the: 

(a) Municipal Treasurer to handle the inventory of PPE and monitoring thereof to prevent opportunities for fraud.

We recommended that management: 

(a) require the ICO-MT to produce the missing funds of ₱252,000.00 and deposit the same to the authorized government depository bank; 

(b) require the ICO-MT and the Municipal Accountant to: (i) perform reconciliation of accounts and records at least quarterly; 

(ii) exert best efforts to locate records pertaining to prior year’s difference of cash balances and prepare adjusting entries thereat; and 

(iii) review reconciling items for proper adjustment in appropriate books; 

(c) apply for the appropriate fidelity bond coverage for the job-order personnel assigned in the collection of market fees; 

(d) continue to improve compliance on the need to update the cashbooks on a daily basis for proper determination of accountabilities; 

(e) instruct the ICO-AMT to refrain from assigning personnel to handle incompatible functions such as disbursing officer who deposits collections of the Municipality; 

(f) require the Municipal Accountant to assign different personnel in processing cash transactions and reconciliations; 

(g) require MT to reflect collections in the RCD and cashbooks on a timely basis; and 

(h) continue to deposit daily and intact the collections.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive: 

(a) require the GPBP focal person of the respective implementing offices to make use of lessons learned from the completed projects to improve efficiency in the implementation of similar NGA-funded projects in the future; 

(b) aim to reduce further unnecessary delays in project implementation to allow the early enjoyment of benefits by the general public; 


(c) ensure that needs and capacity of BHS is properly considered before procurement of medicine/ equipment to assure proper storage/housing thereof to prevent deterioration from non-use and further wastage of government funds; 

(d) maximize the use of distributed equipment by deploying them to needy BHS or other health facility; 

(e) implement control in the management of rice-harvester and four-wheeled tractor by assigning one Municipal employee from the MAO in the monitoring thereof together with the preparation of accomplishment/monitoring reports; 
(f) as far as availability of time and personnel permit, conduct monitoring and validation of the current status of all beneficiaries of “Nego-karts” given accompanied by a report; 

(g) ensure that actual addresses are indicated to facilitate better monitoring of the project; and 

(h) install  sufficient controls  before, during, and after the program is implemented to improve effectiveness of the program and maximization of the use of the funds.

We recommended that management: 

(a) strengthen its recruitment and selection process in hiring job order personnel by reviewing its current workforce, specific work to be done, and objectives before hiring personnel;

(b) reduce the  hiring of personnel whose functions do not contribute to the attainment of the Municipality’s objectives; 

(c) refrain from hiring personnel who is a relative within the fourth civil degree of consanguinity of the appointing or recommending authority unless the nature of the work is highly confidential in nature; 

(d) require the HR Officer to conduct the proper selection and recruitment process such as the conduct of written, oral, and medical examinations  in order to ascertain applicant’s qualifications; 

(e) require the concerned SB official to explain in writing the reasons why their personnel were not regularly reporting to office but stayed only at their residences and those who work on on-call basis; 

(f) require the concerned official to explain in writing the payment of wages of personnel assigned at the personal residences of the official; 


(g) consider reducing the number of job-order personnel at the legislative department; and 

(h) require all department heads to carefully evaluate or assess the need for job order personnel with due consideration on their fitness to the job requirement.

We recommended that Management: 

(a) ensure full completion of the remaining projects identified in the AIP for CY 2017; 

(b) continue to comply with the regulations in the appropriation and utilization thereof; 

(c) continue to implement projects which are capital or investment in nature; 

(d) continue to implement projects on a timely basis to attain desirable socio-economic development and environmental management outcomes of the said fund.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant: 

(a) continue being compliant with the revenue regulations on the withholding of taxes from compensation of employees and creditable taxes for payments to suppliers and contractors and the remittance thereof within the prescribed period; 

(b) continue with the efforts to resolve the carry-over discrepancy on the Due to BIR account balance.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendations that the Municipal Accountant: 

(a) exert further efforts to reconcile employees’ records at GSIS to identify the affected employees on the unremitted accumulated balance of the Due to GSIS account, if any; 

(b) check with the records whether all Personal Share (PS) deducted from the payroll of employees and Government Share (GS) and Employee’s Compensation Contribution (ECC) for all employees were remitted; and; 

(c) cause the immediate remittance to GSIS for the unremitted premiums and contributions of employees, as warranted by the results of the research.

We recommended that the:

ICO Municipal Treasurer produce the missing funds of ₱588,116.16 for deposit to the authorized government depository bank;

Institute appropriate actions on the concerned accountable officer for violation of Article 217 of the Revised Penal Code, if circumstances so warrant; 

require the accountable officers to (i) prepare their own RCD immediately upon remittance to ICO-MT; (ii) post transactions daily in their respective cashbooks; and (iii) ensure that important details are completely indicated in the RCD using the prescribed format.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

conduct exhaustive evaluation of the Due from LGUs account and request for confirmation of receivables from the PTO;

instruct the accounting personnel in-charge of the account to maintain subsidiary ledgers on a regular basis;

keep the financial records of the Municipality properly and completely reflecting all the details necessary to substantiate the accounts in the financial statements; and 

coordinate with the ICO-MT as the MA in CY 2011, who is responsible for the details of the recorded JEV during her term amounting to ₱1,785,873.75.

We recommended that the:

Municipal Accountant ensure (i) the completeness of supporting documents before granting cash advances and the liquidation thereof; (ii) the submission of the certification that the previous CA was already liquidated and recorded in the books;

SB members concerned submit the original certificates of appearance and the other required SDs mentioned above for the identified travels, and written explanation for the negative confirmation received from PCL.

We recommended that: 

the BUB Focal Person of the respective implementing offices (i) strictly monitor the implementation of projects as targeted and planned and take note of any gap for future inputs; (ii) determine reason for  the non-receipt of the funds from the NGAs concerned in order to determine the next steps to be taken by  the LGU in case the project is  no longer be viable; (iii) submit the MOAs with the concerned NGAs; (iv) submit list of targeted beneficiaries per project proposal; (v) prepare profiling of beneficiaries before the project proposal is finalized/submitted for approval of the LCE; 

consider augmenting personnel in the MSWDO and provision of vehicle for fieldwork use in order to facilitate prompt delivery of service and completion/ updating/maintenance of databank of residents/ beneficiaries.

We recommended that the ICO-Municipal Treasurer to 

enforce the specific provisions in Section 255 of R.A. No. 7160 and ensure the uniform application of interest charges on payments of taxpayers with RPT delinquencies;

strictly monitor the issuance of AFs to collecting officers (COs);

verify the accounts of delinquent taxpayers for further collection of interests therefrom; 

require explanations from the COs concerned who had waived the penalties and interests on the payments of certain delinquent taxpayers; and 


enforce applicable sanctions to the erring COs and require recovery of the underpayment of ₱1,261,544.02 from the taxpayers concerned and/or persons deemed liable.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive: 

consider designating another personnel as Business Licensing Officer;


 refrain from assigning the ICO-MT with multiple incompatible functions as well as the other AOs who handle incompatible functions such as the preparation of reports on accountable forms and at the same time performs collecting functions;

submit a written explanation on the inclusion of quarry checkers as “permittees” and those who issue ORs but were not designated as AOs;

require the ICO-MT to (i) submit the missing AF 51 and AF 56 on tables 1 to 5; (ii) explain the discrepancy in physical AF, Abstract of Collections and RCD in table 6 and the discrepancy in the original and duplicate copy of cancelled ORs; (iii) together with the other AOs, regularly update the cashbooks on a daily basis for the proper determination of accountabilities; (iv) re-assess the cash accountabilities of all AOs and apply for the appropriate fidelity bond coverage; (v) along with other AOs, submit the RCD and AFs within the prescribed period; and (vi) stop the practice of allowing the DO to deposit collections in behalf of the ICO-MT; and 

require the AOs to (i) prepare and sign their individual RCD for submission to the ICO-MT upon remittance of collections; and (ii) exercise due care in the preparation of the Abstract of Collections and RCD and include cancelled AF for monitoring, proper accounting and recording.

We recommended that the Municipal Local School Board:

conduct an actual survey on the needs of various school districts especially for additional classrooms, repair and maintenance of school facilities,  and provision of textbooks for school children to serve as a guide in the formulation of the budget; 

carefully plan the SEF Annual Budget that will prioritize capital outlay projects intended for construction/ repair/ maintenance of school buildings, facilities and equipment,  in order to attain the priority objectives of the SEF;

stop the payment of honoraria to teachers without legal basis to support the grant; and 

make representation with LGU and DepEd officials for the inclusion in the annual budget of their General Fund, appropriations for office supplies, other supplies, and other necessary expenses not related to the intentions of the SEF.

We recommended that the Solid Waste Management Board:

adopt applicable measures, starting with an aggressive information campaign in coordination with barangay officials and DepEd officials, to ensure the effective implementation of solid waste management programs particularly the conduct of segregation and collection of wastes at source and undertake best practices in adhering to and fully implementing the provisions of the Ecological Solid Waste Management Act of 2000; 

assign a particular personnel to facilitate the transfer of ownership of the donated lots in Barangay Maliwalu under the name of the Municipality through proper coordination with the donors for the execution of a duly notarized deed of donation; 

conduct frequent consultations with the various sectors of the community for a better development of a Ten-Year Solid Waste Management Plan; and 


conduct regular monitoring of barangays’ compliance with R.A. No. 9003.

We recommended that the Human Resources Management Officer (HRMO): 

review the recruitment and selection process of job order personnel and recommend policies to strengthen the process through consultations with the heads of the different offices for their specific job descriptions and requirements, and objectives;

issue contract of service to job order personnel with job description, term of employment, expected outputs, rate per day, and other pertinent information with conforme of personnel and duly notarized; 

require the presence of all job order personnel for interview and head count at the COA Office and require them to submit PDS and ID, preferably government issued ID. Failure to do so will cause the suspension of salaries given in CY 2015; 

issue identification cards to all legitimate personnel for proper identification;

include the conduct of written, oral, and medical examinations in the recruitment of personnel in order to ascertain applicant’s over-all qualifications; 


reduce the number of quarry checkers, drivers, security-aides, researchers in the legislative offices, and other unnecessary workforce to save on cost of personnel services;

require all heads of offices to objectively assess the performance of personnel for re-hiring purposes; and 

require all job order personnel to submit their PDS to HRO and undergo the process required under the Biometrics System to monitor attendance of personnel, and conduct random check of job order personnel whereabouts on a regular basis and submit attendance reports generated from the Biometrics System to the Accounting Office for the computation of wages.
